00:48:58.730 --> 00:49:04.650
That Chinese government seems
to be advancing quite rapidly

00:49:04.650 --> 00:49:07.290
in quantum communications
with the satellite they have,

00:49:07.290 --> 00:49:09.250
and quantum computing.

00:49:09.250 --> 00:49:13.960
And so I think probably from
our standpoint we would do well

00:49:13.960 --> 00:49:17.820
with, you know, further
investment or focus on it.

00:49:17.820 --> 00:49:20.870
But it's an important
area, I think.

00:49:20.870 --> 00:49:22.170
Oh, yes.

00:49:22.170 --> 00:49:23.970
&gt;&gt; Speaker 2: There's a lot
of talk about a shortage

00:49:23.970 --> 00:49:25.790
of qualified security
professionals

00:49:25.790 --> 00:49:28.010
that [inaudible]
they can't afford

00:49:28.010 --> 00:49:29.310
to pay them [inaudible] wages.

00:49:29.310 --> 00:49:33.780
Are there some recommendations
that you have

00:49:33.780 --> 00:49:38.840
for what [inaudible]
can do to invest better,

00:49:40.110 --> 00:49:41.410
and more particularly
[inaudible] workforce?

00:49:41.410 --> 00:49:42.710
&gt;&gt; J.P. Auffret: Oh.

00:49:42.710 --> 00:49:44.010
I think there's quite
a few things.

00:49:44.010 --> 00:49:51.200
I think part of it is external,
and then part of it's internal.

00:49:51.200 --> 00:49:57.450
So there's -- So the government
has some fantastic programs

00:49:57.450 --> 00:50:03.400
working with the universities
to -- Well, foster --

00:50:03.400 --> 00:50:06.240
enhance education, cyber
security education,

00:50:06.240 --> 00:50:09.020
and also increase the
number of students going

00:50:09.020 --> 00:50:12.100
in to cyber security both in
undergraduate and graduate

00:50:12.100 --> 00:50:14.280
and increasingly K through 12.

00:50:14.280 --> 00:50:22.950
And so I think that the
universities are both training

00:50:22.950 --> 00:50:25.030
and educating a fair number

00:50:25.030 --> 00:50:27.540
of students I don't
think will ever be enough

00:50:27.540 --> 00:50:29.270
because of the issue
with technology.

00:50:29.270 --> 00:50:33.320
But then I think it's
also somewhat difficult

00:50:33.320 --> 00:50:35.210
to join the government.

00:50:35.210 --> 00:50:37.140
So I think for students looking

00:50:37.140 --> 00:50:42.100
to join the government there's
fantastic programs to --

00:50:42.100 --> 00:50:44.300
for internships which
our students do.

00:50:44.300 --> 00:50:50.020
Many of our students have a
challenge with the process,

00:50:50.020 --> 00:50:52.300
although many of the
agencies are very helpful.

00:50:52.300 --> 00:50:53.700
But the long process.

00:50:53.700 --> 00:50:58.760
There's also the chicken and
egg issue with clearances

00:50:58.760 --> 00:51:01.000
that can be a bit
of a challenge.

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:04.720
And then one other thing
I've noticed in the very,

00:51:04.720 --> 00:51:09.830
very large ones, agencies,
is that career pathing --

00:51:09.830 --> 00:51:13.230
Some of the agencies are
fantastic on career pathing

00:51:13.230 --> 00:51:17.070
and cyber, and some not so.

00:51:17.070 --> 00:51:18.430
So I can give two examples.

00:51:18.430 --> 00:51:21.510
Not the name of the
agency, but two examples.

00:51:21.510 --> 00:51:23.500
So one a quite large agency.

00:51:23.500 --> 00:51:29.540
Does fantastic things, but they
-- And this is hard everywhere,

00:51:29.540 --> 00:51:30.840
in private sector companies too.

00:51:30.840 --> 00:51:33.410
Struggling a little
bit with technical

00:51:33.410 --> 00:51:35.790
versus managerial career paths,

00:51:35.790 --> 00:51:40.510
and how to keep somebody
challenged and interested

00:51:40.510 --> 00:51:45.600
and on an advancing career
path in the technical field

00:51:45.600 --> 00:51:48.750
who really loves it and
is really offering a lot.

00:51:48.750 --> 00:51:51.490
Or how someone can try
a managerial career path

00:51:51.490 --> 00:51:52.790
and then go back.

00:51:52.790 --> 00:51:54.910
And so that's hard on a
consulting company too.

00:51:54.910 --> 00:51:56.550
So I think that's an example.

00:51:56.550 --> 00:52:02.550
And another company or agency,
and this is one of the ones

00:52:02.550 --> 00:52:06.760
that does offensive
too, and cyber threat --

00:52:06.760 --> 00:52:12.330
And so their part of the
issue is organizationally

00:52:12.330 --> 00:52:14.020
where the cyber security
group put --

00:52:14.020 --> 00:52:16.070
There's not much
career advancement.

00:52:16.070 --> 00:52:20.130
And that the offensive
is working

00:52:20.130 --> 00:52:22.680
with the more current
technologies.

00:52:22.680 --> 00:52:26.020
So everyone wants to grab
a take towards that too.

00:52:26.020 --> 00:52:29.250
So I think it's a little bit
working with the universities,

00:52:29.250 --> 00:52:31.540
and then a little bit
to ease the way in,

00:52:31.540 --> 00:52:37.370
and then a little bit to --
the career pathing issue.

00:52:37.370 --> 00:52:39.360
What do you think?

00:52:39.360 --> 00:52:40.660
&gt;&gt; Speaker 2: Yeah.

00:52:40.660 --> 00:52:46.350
I know there's a lot of
talk about opening up some

00:52:46.350 --> 00:52:48.620
of the programs like
the [inaudible]

00:52:48.620 --> 00:52:51.380
for [inaudible] two
year institutions

00:52:51.380 --> 00:52:52.830
or even short term programs.

00:52:52.830 --> 00:52:56.380
I don't know.

00:52:56.380 --> 00:52:57.750
&gt;&gt; J.P. Auffret: Well, the
CyberCorps one is fantastic,

00:52:57.750 --> 00:52:59.650
and I think connecting
more towards --

00:52:59.650 --> 00:53:02.380
with the community
colleges would be great.

00:53:02.380 --> 00:53:05.380
The National Science Foundation,
the core competency project

00:53:05.380 --> 00:53:08.160
that we had, that was
a CyberCorps project.

00:53:08.160 --> 00:53:12.370
The community colleges,
they're training

00:53:12.370 --> 00:53:14.080
and working with hands on.

00:53:14.080 --> 00:53:19.600
So I think also too
-- I think there's --

00:53:19.600 --> 00:53:23.130
Well, many I've talked to
it's kind of mixed reviews

00:53:23.130 --> 00:53:26.310
of [inaudible] and the
U.S. digital service,

00:53:26.310 --> 00:53:28.460
but I think those types

00:53:28.460 --> 00:53:34.980
of initiatives have potential
too for cyber security.

00:53:36.990 --> 00:53:41.510
Yeah. So I think all those.

00:53:41.510 --> 00:53:49.150
[ Inaudible ]

00:53:49.150 --> 00:53:50.450
&gt;&gt; J.P. Auffret: Yeah.

00:53:50.450 --> 00:53:52.580
The FDA is quite active.

00:53:52.580 --> 00:53:58.790
Oh. It's cyber security
for medical devices.

00:53:58.790 --> 00:54:01.500
The FDA is quite active in it.

00:54:01.500 --> 00:54:07.690
It's a hard topic, I
think, because part

00:54:07.690 --> 00:54:12.820
of with the approach
to approvals --

00:54:12.820 --> 00:54:20.790
So if a device is similar,
it has a rapid approval

00:54:20.790 --> 00:54:22.890
or an expedited approval path.

00:54:22.890 --> 00:54:25.670
But it's very difficult
to say that software

00:54:25.670 --> 00:54:29.120
on one device is similar to
software on another device.

00:54:29.120 --> 00:54:32.640
But the FDA is looking
at enhanced regulation

00:54:32.640 --> 00:54:37.380
of medical devices according
to the risk obviously.

00:54:37.380 --> 00:54:41.580
And then also some testing
approach for medical devices

00:54:41.580 --> 00:54:43.740
and medical device security.

00:54:43.740 --> 00:54:48.790
And also increased guidance
on issues such as patching.

00:54:48.790 --> 00:54:52.350
So I think all of those, but
it's a real challenging area,

00:54:52.350 --> 00:54:56.950
the -- Everyone see some
of the examples in the news

00:54:56.950 --> 00:54:58.430
over the last years or so

00:54:58.430 --> 00:55:00.210
that got highlighted
with medical devices?

00:55:00.210 --> 00:55:04.100
I think the one that had the
most news play was an infusion

00:55:04.100 --> 00:55:10.240
pump, the drip, where it was
hacked and someone was able

00:55:10.240 --> 00:55:14.220
to turn it on and off remotely.

00:55:14.220 --> 00:55:16.010
They didn't do it,
but they demonstrated

00:55:16.010 --> 00:55:17.610
that it was possible.

00:55:17.610 --> 00:55:22.470
Actually, one of our masters
degree programs we have,

00:55:22.470 --> 00:55:25.150
they have a capstone
class project.

00:55:25.150 --> 00:55:27.030
They did a medical
device project,

00:55:27.030 --> 00:55:32.480
and they tested heart monitors.

00:55:32.480 --> 00:55:36.430
They put it on themselves,
and were able to --

00:55:36.430 --> 00:55:38.550
Some of them had no
security on them.

00:55:38.550 --> 00:55:40.930
They were able to monitor
someone's heart rate

00:55:40.930 --> 00:55:43.460
from like 100 yards away.

00:55:43.460 --> 00:55:46.190
So I think the manufacturers
are getting better,

00:55:46.190 --> 00:55:47.800
but it's a big challenge.

00:55:47.800 --> 00:55:50.200
And it's a big challenge
for the hospitals too.

00:55:50.200 --> 00:55:51.850
I think the hospitals are
going to drive a lot of it,

00:55:51.850 --> 00:55:54.270
and then one thing I
didn't mention is the role

00:55:54.270 --> 00:55:57.260
of insurance and
cyber insurance.

00:55:57.260 --> 00:56:02.690
So cyber insurance is
becoming more and more common.

00:56:02.690 --> 00:56:11.190
And it's being driven partially
by boards to help manage risk.

00:56:11.190 --> 00:56:13.920
It partially provides an
external party that comes in

00:56:13.920 --> 00:56:17.540
and does underwriting
assessment in some manner.

00:56:17.540 --> 00:56:22.550
So it helps you benchmark, but
I think it also has an impact

00:56:22.550 --> 00:56:25.620
on medical device companies
who are selling medical devices

00:56:25.620 --> 00:56:28.020
that could have a problem.

00:56:28.020 --> 00:56:31.050
Federal Trade Commission
too has a very large role.

00:56:31.050 --> 00:56:34.390
But it's a big issue.

00:56:34.390 --> 00:56:36.050
Oh, yes?

00:56:36.050 --> 00:56:39.380
&gt;&gt; Speaker 4: I don't know that
I want to focus on [inaudible]

00:56:39.380 --> 00:56:44.780
but it seems that cyber is an
area where [inaudible] ahead.

00:56:44.780 --> 00:56:47.370
You can't afford to fall
behind if you invest more

00:56:47.370 --> 00:56:52.240
and more resources in
just maintaining what you

00:56:52.240 --> 00:56:54.120
already have.

00:56:54.120 --> 00:57:01.030
Is that -- Do you see
that having an effect

00:57:01.030 --> 00:57:04.320
on rate of implementation?

00:57:04.320 --> 00:57:06.990
Some countries may be
[inaudible] investments.

00:57:06.990 --> 00:57:08.290
And then [inaudible].

00:57:08.290 --> 00:57:09.590
&gt;&gt; J.P. Auffret: That's
an interesting question

00:57:09.590 --> 00:57:11.160
because I think it
ties to the role of ICT

00:57:11.160 --> 00:57:12.560
in a country and in society.

00:57:12.560 --> 00:57:16.880
So I think every
country faces a risk.

00:57:16.880 --> 00:57:24.420
If -- As Japan is moving towards
society 5.0 and Singapore

00:57:24.420 --> 00:57:28.670
and Estonia and us,
that countries

00:57:28.670 --> 00:57:32.770
who aren't ICT oriented
risk falling further

00:57:32.770 --> 00:57:34.590
and further behind and
becoming less competitive.

00:57:34.590 --> 00:57:40.410
And so given that, and given
how important cyber security is,

00:57:40.410 --> 00:57:42.680
I think it's imperative
for the countries

00:57:42.680 --> 00:57:44.840
to be cyber security
oriented too.

00:57:44.840 --> 00:57:47.770
What holds them back,
though, is partially cost.

00:57:47.770 --> 00:57:52.550
So a lot of the technologies
are very, very expensive,

00:57:52.550 --> 00:57:53.870
and take some expertise.

00:57:53.870 --> 00:57:59.600
So the countries
have a challenge both

00:57:59.600 --> 00:58:04.770
with the new ICT they're doing,
but also in the cost and how

00:58:04.770 --> 00:58:07.730
to go about the cyber security.

00:58:07.730 --> 00:58:14.330
There's -- Through
-- ITU in Singapore.

00:58:14.330 --> 00:58:16.920
There's a group who has a focus

00:58:16.920 --> 00:58:23.400
on open source cyber
security tools.

00:58:23.400 --> 00:58:25.800
There's many, and they
don't do everything,

00:58:25.800 --> 00:58:27.100
but they do some things, and --

00:58:27.100 --> 00:58:31.190
But there's a challenge
of putting them together.

00:58:31.190 --> 00:58:32.790
But there's that challenge too.

00:58:32.790 --> 00:58:37.330
Many, many companies now have
30 or 40 technologies that --

00:58:37.330 --> 00:58:39.930
sometimes which conflict.

00:58:39.930 --> 00:58:43.820
And so some of the research
now is in company initiatives

00:58:43.820 --> 00:58:46.080
or using the phrase
orchestrating cyber security

00:58:46.080 --> 00:58:49.570
technologies so they're
compatible.

00:58:52.510 --> 00:59:08.220
[ Inaudible ]

00:59:08.220 --> 00:59:09.520
&gt;&gt; J.P. Auffret: Oh.

00:59:09.520 --> 00:59:10.820
I have an opinion.

00:59:10.820 --> 00:59:13.510
I don't think so.

00:59:13.510 --> 00:59:20.550
I don't think there's
-- I don't think the --

00:59:20.550 --> 00:59:25.690
I don't think there would be the
national will that it would take

00:59:25.690 --> 00:59:32.240
to actually do that, given how
we're organized and the role

00:59:32.240 --> 00:59:35.020
of the private sector
and things like that.

00:59:35.020 --> 00:59:36.840
So I don't think.

00:59:36.840 --> 00:59:38.600
But it's a really
fascinating question.

00:59:38.600 --> 00:59:42.840
The electronic medical
record, the value of it is --

00:59:42.840 --> 00:59:46.450
on the black market is much
higher than a credit card.

00:59:46.450 --> 00:59:48.980
So credit card is
relatively low.

00:59:48.980 --> 00:59:51.730
But medical record much,

00:59:51.730 --> 00:59:55.700
much higher because if you steal
someone's medical record it will

00:59:55.700 --> 00:59:57.850
be -- You can put
bills through on it.

00:59:57.850 --> 01:00:01.000
It will be six months
before it's caught.

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:03.400
A credit card might be
stopped the next day,

01:00:03.400 --> 01:00:05.220
but you can Medicaid
or Medicare fraud

01:00:05.220 --> 01:00:07.690
or insurance fraud
six months or a year.

01:00:07.690 --> 01:00:10.050
So it's much more valuable.

01:00:10.050 --> 01:00:12.330
One kind of note on that.

01:00:12.330 --> 01:00:16.250
In Virginia, 7 of the 10
largest hospitals have Epic.

01:00:16.250 --> 01:00:18.480
The Epic electronic
medical records system.

01:00:18.480 --> 01:00:21.140
But they're for the most
part on different versions.

01:00:21.140 --> 01:00:24.670
So they're not compatible
amongst each other.

